  <AdminHelpDoc title="Recruiting Webinar — April 28, 2026" tag="Reference">
    <p><strong>Panelists:</strong> Adam Glickman (Firecrackers), Tori Lewis (Lady Dukes / Blue Magic), Donny (Finesse Fastpitch)<br />
    <strong>Source:</strong> <a href="https://x.com/thealliancefp/status/2047334946922983773" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">x.com/thealliancefp/status/2047334946922983773</a></p>

    <h2>TL;DR</h2>
    <p>Spring is the work; summer is the harvest — coaches show up to events with a "shopping list" already built, so being on it requires emails, video, school research, and camps done <strong>before</strong> June. Once a coach is at your game, you've already passed the athleticism bar; what they're evaluating is character, body language after failure, leadership, and how you handle a strikeout — not your slash line. NIL and rev-share for softball are mostly noise (98% of programs have crumbs), the transfer portal has tightened roster spots, and the strongest filter against the chaos is honest evaluation: cast a wide net (D1 through NAIA / JUCO), pick schools by fit not name, and "drive your own bus" — though clubs disagree on how hands-on they should be.</p>

    <h2>Webinar Takeaways → Stars POV</h2>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>#</th><th>Webinar said</th><th>Stars take</th><th>Action</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>1</td><td><strong>"Be the butter."</strong> Spring is when you get on the coach's ingredient list. Weekly video, targeted emails, school research, camps. June/July is execution, not discovery.</td><td><strong>Agree, full stop.</strong> This is the framework we'll anchor camp on. Today is May 1 — we have ~5 weeks before Show Me The Money in Newberry. Every player needs a content + outreach cadence by May 9.</td><td>Camp anchor concept.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>2</td><td><strong>"Control the controllables."</strong> Coaches recruit character — hustle, body language, picking up the dugout, eye contact with parents. They cross kids off the list for stuff that has nothing to do with stats.</td><td><strong>Agree.</strong> Most important thing parents need to hear, because it's where they accidentally hurt their kid.</td><td>Camp talking point. Parent email lead.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>3</td><td><strong>"Game of failure."</strong> A .300 hitter is great. Coaches recruit how you handle the 7-out-of-10.</td><td><strong>Agree.</strong> Reframes pressure. Use this language with players who freeze at showcases.</td><td>Camp story.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>4</td><td><strong>"Drive your own bus."</strong> Player owns the process — research, emails, camps. Club coach is the assistant, not the driver. Adam said: <em>"It is not the club coach's responsibility to get kids recruited."</em></td><td><strong>Disagree, partially.</strong> The player has to drive on <strong>effort, character, communication.</strong> But Stars takes responsibility for <strong>advocacy, school list, coach relationships, tracking, follow-up.</strong> As Stars' recruiting coordinator, getting our kids scholarships <strong>is</strong> my job. The webinar's "you're on your own" framing is what most clubs hide behind. We don't.</td><td>Camp talking point. Recruiting differentiator vs. other clubs.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>5</td><td><strong>"Be the calm voice."</strong> Recruiting is a rollercoaster — anxiety, mental health, comparison. Club leaders should be the steady hand.</td><td><strong>Agree.</strong> Especially for parents.</td><td>Tone-setter throughout.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>6</td><td><strong>"Honesty is your currency with college coaches."</strong> Don't oversell. If you tell a coach a kid is coachable, she'd better be. Reputation matters more than any single placement.</td><td><strong>Agree, hard.</strong> This <em>is</em> our pitch to other players too — we don't burn coach relationships, so when we vouch for you, it lands.</td><td>Says it out loud at camp.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>7</td><td><strong>"Cast a wide net. D1-or-bust is dead."</strong> 1300+ programs. Most kids only know the top 35. Honest evaluation: where do you actually fit?</td><td><strong>Agree.</strong> This is where program-match lives — discovering programs families have never heard of. Tori's example: kid whose top school was Texas A&M because <em>"they were the first school to look at me"</em> — funny, painful, our daily reality.</td><td>Use verbatim with parents. Inform program-match buildout.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>8</td><td><strong>"Player drives the bus, parents step back."</strong> Don't carry the gear. Don't make eye contact for approval. Don't email the tournament director for a coach list.</td><td><strong>Agree, but tactful delivery.</strong> Parents don't want to hear they're hurting the process. Frame as: <em>"Here's what coaches see. Here's how we help you stay in your lane."</em></td><td>Parent email + parent-focused camp segment.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>9</td><td><strong>NIL / rev-share reality.</strong> Post-House settlement, ~100 schools have meaningful money. 80-90% goes to football and basketball. For 98% of softball recruits, NIL is noise + distraction.</td><td><strong>Agree.</strong> Cut through the noise. Don't let kids/parents pick schools chasing rumored NIL crumbs.</td><td>Quick mention only. Goal is to <em>deflate</em> the noise, not amplify it.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>10</td><td><strong>Transfer portal has tightened roster spots.</strong> Roster limits + rev-share + portal = coaches recruiting differently. Less in-person, more video + Game Changer + Sports Recruits.</td><td><strong>Agree.</strong> Means our digital footprint (video, profile pages, tracked links) matters more, not less.</td><td>Reinforces why infrastructure investment is correct.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>11</td><td><strong>Walk up to coaches at tournaments and ask: <em>"Coach, what are you looking for?"</em></strong> Don't lead with your roster. (Donny)</td><td><strong>Agree.</strong> Adopt verbatim for tournament behavior.</td><td>Tournament playbook.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>12</td><td><strong>The "potential" trap.</strong> "Potential" means you haven't done it yet. (Tori) Don't get drunk on rankings — top-25, top-65 lists.</td><td><strong>Agree.</strong> Steal Tori's framing.</td><td>Camp talking point.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>13</td><td><strong>Have a "why."</strong> Tori's example: kid said top school was Texas A&M because <em>they were the first school to look at me</em>. Not a why.</td><td><strong>Agree.</strong> Every uncommitted player needs to articulate her why for each top school by camp.</td><td>Camp homework.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>14</td><td><strong>Use platforms (Sports Recruits, College Bound Jocks, APS) but don't outsource judgment.</strong> They distribute, you decide.</td><td><strong>Agree.</strong> We use them — but our advocacy + tracking goes further.</td><td>Note for parents who ask.</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h2>What We're NOT Doing (deliberately)</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Not adopting the hands-off "just drive the bus" framing.</strong> That's how clubs avoid accountability. We take the heat.</li>
      <li><strong>Not hyping NIL.</strong> Don't want parents picking schools chasing rumored money.</li>
      <li><strong>Not promising D1.</strong> Wide net or nothing.</li>
      <li><strong>Not running mass emails to coaches.</strong> Every email is targeted, with a tracked link, and a specific reason for sending.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Lessons That Inform Stars Infrastructure</h2>
    <table>
      <thead><tr><th>Lesson</th><th>What we built / are building</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>Coaches don't browse — they hunt by name</td><td>Per-player profile pages with the Stars pixel that feeds <strong>program-match</strong>. program-match owns the CRM: outreach_threads, outreach_messages, heat scores, send/reply log.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Honesty is currency</td><td>program-match logs every email per thread so we stay consistent across coaches and over time.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Spring is the work</td><td>Camp May 9 anchors the cadence; weekly video expectation set with parents.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Cast a wide net</td><td>program-match — discovery + match scoring for D2/D3/NAIA/JUCO programs.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Body language matters</td><td>Parent education + on-field reminders, not a tech build.</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
